<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="16" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1039,2037]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1471,1496]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[352,456,1471,1496]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Holotype</typeStatus>
(LACM 2602; 
<figureCitation box="[634,754,1471,1496]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[173,1414,196,895]" captionTargetId="figure-537@15.[169,1417,193,898]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pherusa andersonorum n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 2602), oblique lateral view. B. Same, anterior end, ventral view showing ventral pharyngeal organ. C. Paratype (LACM 2603), anterior end, dorsal view, methyl green staining. D. Same, head, partly everted (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Another paratype with one palp and all branchiae preserved (Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). F. Another paratype, cross section of a medial segment. G. Same, chaetiger 5, right neurochaetae. H. Same, chaetiger 20, right neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 2.7 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.1 mm, D: 0.3 mm, E: 0.7 mm, F: 0.25 mm, G: 50 µm, H: 46 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951894" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951894/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 3A, B</figureCitation>
) complete; body cylindrical, slightly tapered posteriorly; 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="21.0">21 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[271,360,1508,1533]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="2.8">2.8 mm</quantity>
wide, cephalic cage 
<quantity box="[606,674,1508,1533]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
long, 43 chaetigers. Papillae with sand particles, especially along dorsal anterior papillae (
<figureCitation box="[434,526,1543,1568]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[173,1414,196,895]" captionTargetId="figure-537@15.[169,1417,193,898]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pherusa andersonorum n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 2602), oblique lateral view. B. Same, anterior end, ventral view showing ventral pharyngeal organ. C. Paratype (LACM 2603), anterior end, dorsal view, methyl green staining. D. Same, head, partly everted (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Another paratype with one palp and all branchiae preserved (Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). F. Another paratype, cross section of a medial segment. G. Same, chaetiger 5, right neurochaetae. H. Same, chaetiger 20, right neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 2.7 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.1 mm, D: 0.3 mm, E: 0.7 mm, F: 0.25 mm, G: 50 µm, H: 46 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951894" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951894/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
); anterior notochaetae with epizoic ciliates (
<figureCitation box="[1041,1130,1543,1568]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[173,1414,196,895]" captionTargetId="figure-537@15.[169,1417,193,898]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pherusa andersonorum n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 2602), oblique lateral view. B. Same, anterior end, ventral view showing ventral pharyngeal organ. C. Paratype (LACM 2603), anterior end, dorsal view, methyl green staining. D. Same, head, partly everted (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Another paratype with one palp and all branchiae preserved (Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). F. Another paratype, cross section of a medial segment. G. Same, chaetiger 5, right neurochaetae. H. Same, chaetiger 20, right neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 2.7 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.1 mm, D: 0.3 mm, E: 0.7 mm, F: 0.25 mm, G: 50 µm, H: 46 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951894" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951894/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
). Papillae arranged in 3–4 alternating transverse series.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1039,2037]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Cephalic hood not exposed. Prostomium (observed in 
<typeStatus box="[812,921,1615,1640]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">paratypes</typeStatus>
) low cone; four red eyes, anterior ones larger (
<figureCitation box="[159,287,1652,1677]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[173,1414,196,895]" captionTargetId="figure-537@15.[169,1417,193,898]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pherusa andersonorum n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 2602), oblique lateral view. B. Same, anterior end, ventral view showing ventral pharyngeal organ. C. Paratype (LACM 2603), anterior end, dorsal view, methyl green staining. D. Same, head, partly everted (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Another paratype with one palp and all branchiae preserved (Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). F. Another paratype, cross section of a medial segment. G. Same, chaetiger 5, right neurochaetae. H. Same, chaetiger 20, right neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 2.7 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.1 mm, D: 0.3 mm, E: 0.7 mm, F: 0.25 mm, G: 50 µm, H: 46 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951894" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951894/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 3D, E</figureCitation>
). Caruncle short. Palps large, 1.5–2.0 x longer and wider than branchiae; palp keels rounded, low. Lateral lips well developed; ventral and dorsal lips reduced.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1039,2037]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Branchiae cirriform (
<figureCitation box="[442,532,1724,1749]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[173,1414,196,895]" captionTargetId="figure-537@15.[169,1417,193,898]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pherusa andersonorum n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 2602), oblique lateral view. B. Same, anterior end, ventral view showing ventral pharyngeal organ. C. Paratype (LACM 2603), anterior end, dorsal view, methyl green staining. D. Same, head, partly everted (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Another paratype with one palp and all branchiae preserved (Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). F. Another paratype, cross section of a medial segment. G. Same, chaetiger 5, right neurochaetae. H. Same, chaetiger 20, right neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 2.7 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.1 mm, D: 0.3 mm, E: 0.7 mm, F: 0.25 mm, G: 50 µm, H: 46 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951894" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951894/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
); four filaments arranged in a single row, two lateral pairs with two filaments each; filaments smaller and thinner than palps. Nephridial lobes short, placed below inner (third counting from the dorsalmost) branchiae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1039,2037]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Cephalic cage chaetae about ¼ as long as body, twice as long as body width. Chaetigers 1–3 forming cephalic cage; chaetae arranged in short series, dorsolateral in chaetiger 1, become lateral in chaetigers 2–3. About 10 noto- and 8 neurochaetae in chaetiger 1, 8 and 
<quantity box="[609,652,1903,1928]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="in" value="6.0">6 in</quantity>
chaetiger 2, and 6 and 
<quantity box="[912,955,1903,1928]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="in" value="5.0">5 in</quantity>
chaetiger 3.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1039,2037]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Anterior dorsal margin of first chaetiger with a trilobed, low projection (better developed in 
<typeStatus box="[1268,1378,1940,1964]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">paratypes</typeStatus>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[173,1414,196,895]" captionTargetId="figure-537@15.[169,1417,193,898]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pherusa andersonorum n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 2602), oblique lateral view. B. Same, anterior end, ventral view showing ventral pharyngeal organ. C. Paratype (LACM 2603), anterior end, dorsal view, methyl green staining. D. Same, head, partly everted (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Another paratype with one palp and all branchiae preserved (Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). F. Another paratype, cross section of a medial segment. G. Same, chaetiger 5, right neurochaetae. H. Same, chaetiger 20, right neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 2.7 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.1 mm, D: 0.3 mm, E: 0.7 mm, F: 0.25 mm, G: 50 µm, H: 46 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951894" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951894/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Chaetigers 1–3 of about the same length. Chaetal transition from cephalic cage to body chaetae abrupt; anchylosed, falcate blunt neurohooks from chaetiger 4. Gonopodial lobes not seen.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951894" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4951894" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951894/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" startId="15.[151,250,920,942]" targetBox="[173,1414,196,895]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,920,1095]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,277,920,942]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">FIGURE 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[286,527,920,942]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="andersonorum" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[286,527,920,942]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Pherusa andersonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[535,594,920,942]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[535,588,920,942]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">n. sp</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
A. Holotype (LACM 2602), oblique lateral view. B. Same, anterior end, ventral view showing ventral pharyngeal organ. C. Paratype (LACM 2603), anterior end, dorsal view, methyl green staining. D. Same, head, partly everted (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Another paratype with one palp and all branchiae preserved (Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). F. Another paratype, cross section of a medial segment. G. Same, chaetiger 5, right neurochaetae. H. Same, chaetiger 20, right neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 2.7 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.1 mm, D: 0.3 mm, E: 0.7 mm, F: 0.25 mm, G: 50 µm, H: 46 µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1440,1134,2026]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Parapodia poorly developed, chaetae emerge from body wall. Parapodia lateral; medial neuropodia ventrolateral (
<figureCitation box="[309,396,1170,1195]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[173,1414,196,895]" captionTargetId="figure-537@15.[169,1417,193,898]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pherusa andersonorum n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 2602), oblique lateral view. B. Same, anterior end, ventral view showing ventral pharyngeal organ. C. Paratype (LACM 2603), anterior end, dorsal view, methyl green staining. D. Same, head, partly everted (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Another paratype with one palp and all branchiae preserved (Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). F. Another paratype, cross section of a medial segment. G. Same, chaetiger 5, right neurochaetae. H. Same, chaetiger 20, right neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 2.7 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.1 mm, D: 0.3 mm, E: 0.7 mm, F: 0.25 mm, G: 50 µm, H: 46 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951894" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951894/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
). Notopodial lobes low, with one pre- and two long postchaetal papillae. Neuropodia lobes lower with one anterior, two posterior, and an inferior long papillae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1440,1134,2026]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Medial notochaetae arranged in a È-pattern, transverse to body axis, directed dorsally. All notochaetae multiarticulated capillaries, articles short basally, medium-sized medially, long distally; about 8 per fascicle, as long as body width, longer in posterior chaetigers. Neurochaetae multiarticulated capillaries in chaetigers 1–3; falcate anchylosed neurohooks from chaetiger 4, arranged in transverse series (
<figureCitation box="[1048,1138,1350,1375]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[173,1414,196,895]" captionTargetId="figure-537@15.[169,1417,193,898]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pherusa andersonorum n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 2602), oblique lateral view. B. Same, anterior end, ventral view showing ventral pharyngeal organ. C. Paratype (LACM 2603), anterior end, dorsal view, methyl green staining. D. Same, head, partly everted (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Another paratype with one palp and all branchiae preserved (Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). F. Another paratype, cross section of a medial segment. G. Same, chaetiger 5, right neurochaetae. H. Same, chaetiger 20, right neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 2.7 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.1 mm, D: 0.3 mm, E: 0.7 mm, F: 0.25 mm, G: 50 µm, H: 46 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951894" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951894/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 3G</figureCitation>
), 3 neurohooks anteriorly, becoming smaller, thicker, darker (
<figureCitation box="[541,630,1386,1411]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[173,1414,196,895]" captionTargetId="figure-537@15.[169,1417,193,898]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pherusa andersonorum n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 2602), oblique lateral view. B. Same, anterior end, ventral view showing ventral pharyngeal organ. C. Paratype (LACM 2603), anterior end, dorsal view, methyl green staining. D. Same, head, partly everted (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Another paratype with one palp and all branchiae preserved (Pa: palp, VPO: ventral pharyngeal organ). F. Another paratype, cross section of a medial segment. G. Same, chaetiger 5, right neurochaetae. H. Same, chaetiger 20, right neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 2.7 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.1 mm, D: 0.3 mm, E: 0.7 mm, F: 0.25 mm, G: 50 µm, H: 46 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951894" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951894/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 3H</figureCitation>
), up to 4 posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1440,1134,2026]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Posterior end with long chaetae, notochaetae twice as long as body width; pygidium conical, truncate, anus depressed, terminal; without cirri.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1440,1134,2026]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,1494,1519]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Variation.</emphasis>
The smallest 
<typeStatus box="[481,577,1495,1519]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">paratype</typeStatus>
(
<quantity box="[594,684,1494,1519]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="7.5">7.5 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[758,825,1494,1519]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
wide, cephalic cage 
<quantity box="[1067,1155,1494,1519]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
long, 31 chaetigers) has hooks with tips pale, depressed, thin, in chaetiger 4 and present through 10 chaetigers; they are replaced from the dorsalmost by dark anchylosed neurohooks, with the inferior hook the last to be replaced. This specimen had only 6 notochaetae per bundle in medial chaetigers. Other 
<typeStatus box="[769,879,1603,1627]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">paratypes</typeStatus>
, being twice as large (
<quantity box="[1141,1223,1602,1627]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[1298,1366,1602,1627]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
wide, cephalic cage 
<quantity box="[312,378,1638,1663]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
long, 40 chaetigers), have some similar neurohooks in fewer anterior neuropodia; the largest 
<typeStatus box="[151,247,1675,1699]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">paratype</typeStatus>
(
<quantity box="[266,349,1674,1699]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="22.0">22 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[427,495,1674,1699]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
wide, cephalic cage 
<quantity box="[742,811,1674,1699]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
long, 48 chaetigers) however, lacks them completely. Many 
<typeStatus box="[223,330,1711,1735]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">paratypes</typeStatus>
have their anterior end everted because they were narcotized with MgCl 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1144,1152,1725,1739]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">2</subScript>
; several were mature.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1440,1134,2026]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1749,1774]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[321,583,1749,1774]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="andersonorum" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[321,583,1749,1774]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Pherusa andersonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[590,652,1749,1774]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[590,652,1749,1774]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
belongs to the group of species whose dorsal body papillae have sand particles on them. This group also includes 
<taxonomicName authority="(Stimpson, 1854)" authorityName="NW" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[646,955,1785,1810]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="aspera">
<emphasis box="[646,751,1786,1809]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. aspera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Stimpson, W." box="[767,947,1785,1810]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 67" refId="ref51068" refString="Stimpson, W. (1854) Synopsis of the marine Invertebrata of Grand Manan, or the region about the mouth of the Bay of Fundy, New Brunswick. Smithsonian Contributions to Knowledge, 6, 1 - 67. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 30062" type="journal article" year="1854">Stimpson, 1854</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Quatrefages, 1866" authorityName="de Quatrefages" authorityYear="1866" box="[968,1324,1785,1810]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="incrustata">
<emphasis box="[968,1109,1786,1809]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. incrustata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Quatrefages, A. de" box="[1118,1324,1785,1810]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="578 - 600" refId="ref50228" refString="Quatrefages, A. de (1866 (1865 )) Histoire Naturelle des Anneles Marins et d'Eau Douce: Annelides et Gephyriens. Tome Premier. Collection des Suites a Buffon formant avec les Oeuvres de cet auteur un Cours Complet d'Histoire Naturelle. Librairie Encyclopedique de Roret, Paris, 588 pp [Wright, E. P. (1866) Annelida. Zoological Record, Section 6 (Annelida, etc.), 578 - 600.]" type="book chapter" year="1866">Quatrefages, 1866</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
reinst., 
<taxonomicName authority="Hartman, 1961" authorityName="Hartman" authorityYear="1961" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="neopapillata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. neopapillata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hartman, O." box="[301,473,1821,1846]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 226" refId="ref48061" refString="Hartman, O. (1961) Polychaetous annelids from California. Allan Hancock Pacific Expeditions, 25, 1 - 226." type="journal article" year="1961">Hartman, 1961</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Quatrefages, 1849" authorityName="Quatrefages" authorityYear="1849" box="[538,874,1821,1846]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis box="[538,657,1821,1846]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. obscura</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Quatrefages, A. de" box="[668,874,1821,1846]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="277 - 306" refId="ref50160" refString="Quatrefages, A. de (1849) Etudes sur les types inferieurs de l'embranchment des Anneles. Memoire sur la Famille des Chloremiens, Chloraemea, Nob. Annales des Sciences Naturelles, Troisieme Serie (Zoologie), 12, 277 - 306, pls. 9 - 10. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 51505" type="journal article" year="1849">Quatrefages, 1849</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
reinst. However, the only two species with sand particles present throughout the body are 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[607,796,1857,1882]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="andersonorum" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[607,796,1857,1882]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. andersonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[802,863,1857,1882]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[802,863,1857,1882]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="NW" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[916,1019,1858,1881]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="aspera">
<emphasis box="[916,1019,1858,1881]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and despite their resemblance to each other, they differ in the relative number of neurohooks in medial and posterior chaetigers. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[1172,1361,1893,1918]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="andersonorum" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1172,1361,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. andersonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1367,1429,1893,1918]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1367,1429,1893,1918]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, there are 3–4 neurohooks (body 
<quantity box="[507,592,1929,1954]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="2.8">2.8 mm</quantity>
wide), whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="NW" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[772,874,1930,1953]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="aspera">
<emphasis box="[772,874,1930,1953]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has more neurohooks per bundle (5–6; body 
<quantity box="[1372,1437,1929,1954]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
wide). These two species are found in different habitats: 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[807,999,1965,1990]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="andersonorum" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[807,999,1965,1990]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. andersonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1009,1074,1965,1990]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1009,1074,1965,1990]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, lives in dead kelp holdfasts in subtidal rocky bottoms, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="NW" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[516,619,2002,2025]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="aspera">
<emphasis box="[516,619,2002,2025]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
thrives in shelly bottoms in depths to 
<quantity box="[1040,1097,2001,2026]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="m" value="45.0">45 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Appy, T. D. &amp; Linkletter, L. E. &amp; Dadswell, M. J." box="[1111,1338,2001,2026]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 124" refId="ref46143" refString="Appy, T. D., Linkletter, L. E. &amp; Dadswell, M. J. (1980) Annelida: Polychaeta. In: A Guide to the Marine Flora and Fauna of the Bay of Fundy. Canada, Fisheries and Marine Service, Technical Report, 920, pp. i - vi + pp. 1 - 124." type="book chapter" year="1980">
Appy 
<emphasis box="[1181,1237,2001,2026]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al.</emphasis>
1980:33
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,151,357]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,151,176]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named after Genevieve and Shane Anderson, enthusiastic marine biologists formerly working at Santa Barbara City College and University of 
<collectingRegion box="[917,1034,188,213]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">California</collectingRegion>
, Santa Barbara, respectively. It is a modest homage to their achievements in teaching and research, and to thank them for their support by collecting and providing the means to study their materials. The epithet is a plural noun in the genitive case.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1411,295,320]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,151,357]" box="[199,1411,295,320]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<materialsCitation box="[199,1407,295,320]" country="United States of America" elevation="12" location="Off Santa Barbara" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="California" typeStatus="holotype">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,357,295,320]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,295,320]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Type</typeStatus>
